\description{
Extends the individual-sampling rarefaction of \code{\link[=itv_accumulation]{itv_accumulation()}} from a
single per-species trait metric to \strong{community-level functional diversity
indices}: it asks how many individuals must be sampled \emph{per species}
before each functional diversity index of the assemblage stabilises. For
each sampling effort \code{n} (individuals per species), \code{n_perm} balanced
sub-samples of \code{n} individuals per species are drawn without replacement,
pooled into one assemblage, projected into a fixed trait space (a single
PCA computed once on all individuals, so indices stay comparable across
efforts, as in \code{\link[=bootstrap_functional_space]{bootstrap_functional_space()}}), and every requested index
is recomputed. The draws are summarised by their mean and a resampling
quantile band.
}
\details{
Entities are \strong{individuals} (so the indices are sensitive to intraspecific
variability), pooled into a single unweighted assemblage. Rarefaction is
\emph{balanced}: only species with at least \code{min_n} complete individuals are
kept, and effort is capped at the smallest retained species' size, so every
species contributes exactly \code{n} individuals at every effort level and no
species-richness effect is confounded with sampling effort.

As in \code{\link[=itv_accumulation]{itv_accumulation()}}, the meaning of "stabilises" depends on the kind
of index:

\describe{
\item{\strong{Accumulation index} (\code{"fric"})}{Functional richness (the convex
hull volume of the pooled individuals) genuinely rises with \code{n} and
saturates. A Michaelis-Menten or negative-exponential model is fitted
and \verb{n*} is the effort reaching \code{asymptote_prop} of the fitted
asymptote. A near-flat or ill-conditioned curve can send the fitted
asymptote to implausible values; a fit whose asymptote exceeds
\code{max_extrap_factor} times the observed maximum is rejected and reported
as \code{"accumulation (no asymptote identified)"}, with the observed curve
still returned.}
\item{\strong{Convergence indices} (\code{"fdis"}, \code{"rao"}, \code{"feve"}, \code{"fdiv"})}{
Dispersion / regularity indices are (near-)unbiased in expectation, so
their mean is essentially flat and what stabilises is \emph{precision}: \verb{n*}
is the smallest \code{n} beyond which the resampling band's relative
half-width stays at or below \code{conv_tol}.}
}

Index engines. \code{"fdis"} (functional dispersion, the mean distance of
individuals to their centroid; Laliberte & Legendre, 2010) and \code{"rao"}
(Rao's quadratic entropy, the mean pairwise distance; Botta-Dukat, 2005)
are computed directly. \code{"feve"} (functional evenness) and \code{"fdiv"}
(functional divergence; Villeger et al., 2008) are delegated to
\code{\link[FD:dbFD]{FD::dbFD()}} and are only available when the (Suggested) \code{FD} package is
installed. \code{"fric"} is functional \strong{richness}, and -- like
\code{\link[=bootstrap_functional_space]{bootstrap_functional_space()}} -- how it is measured is controlled by
\code{method}: the convex-hull volume (\code{"convexhull"}, the default FRic of
Villeger et al., 2008), the total branch length of a UPGMA functional
dendrogram (\code{"dendrogram"}, Petchey & Gaston, 2002), the Trait Probability
Density richness (\code{"tpd"}, Carmona et al., 2019) or a Gaussian-kernel
hypervolume (\code{"hypervolume"}, Blonder et al., 2014). The kernel/grid used by
\code{"tpd"} and \code{"hypervolume"} is fixed once from the full individual set so
the richness stays comparable across efforts (as in
\code{\link[=bootstrap_functional_space]{bootstrap_functional_space()}}). Requested but unavailable indices/methods
(missing Suggested package) are dropped with a message.

The \code{n_perm} draws at each effort are independent and are distributed across
\code{future.apply}'s workers when that (Suggested) package is installed and a
parallel \code{\link[future:plan]{future::plan()}} is set, exactly as in
\code{\link[=bootstrap_functional_space]{bootstrap_functional_space()}}; otherwise they run sequentially with
identical results.
}
